HEADWORD: Sere
<hw>Sere</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧r)</pr>, }</mhw>
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>seer</ets>, AS. <ets>se⟦aacute⟧r</ets>
(assumed) fr. <ets>se⟦aacute⟧rian</ets> to wither; akin to D.
<ets>zoor</ets> dry, LG. <ets>soor</ets>, OHG. <ets>sor⟦emac⟧n</ets> to
wither, Gr. <grk>a"y`ein</grk> to parch, to dry, Skr.
<ets>⟦cced⟧ush</ets> (for <ets>sush</ets>) to dry, to wither, Zend
<ets>hush</ets> to dry. ⟦root⟧152. Cf. <er>Austere</er>,
<er>Sorrel</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>Dry; withered; no longer
green; -- applied to leaves.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have lived long enough; my way of life⟦br⟧
Is fall'n into the <qex>sear</qex>, the yellow leaf.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sear</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sere
<hw>Sere</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dry; withered. Same as
<er>Sear</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But with its sound it shook the sails⟦br⟧
That were so thin and <qex>sere</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

